Do telomere dynamics link lifestyle and lifespan?

Monaghan P(1), Haussmann MF.

Author information:
(1)Division of Environmental & Evolutionary Biology, Institute of Biomedical and 
Life Sciences, Glasgow University, Glasgow G12 8QQ, UK. P.Monaghan@bio.gla.ac.uk

Identifying and understanding the processes that underlie the observed variation 
in lifespan within and among species remains one of the central areas of 
biological research. Questions directed at how, at what rate and why organisms 
grow old and die link disciplines such as evolutionary ecology to those of cell 
biology and gerontology. One process now thought to have a key role in ageing is 
the pattern of erosion of the protective ends of chromosomes, the telomeres. 
Here, we discuss what is currently known about the factors influencing telomere 
regulation, and how this relates to fundamental questions about the relationship 
between lifestyle and lifespan.

